---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { absoluteUrl } from '../../i18n/utils';

const lang = 'en';
const title = 'Novel — Genesis: The Disappearance of the Founder and the Promise';
const description = 'A historical fiction about the disappearance of Satoshi Nakamoto. Built on the primary sources archived by Bitcoin Institute, the novel reads the silence of one developer and the choices he left behind.';
---

<BaseLayout
  title={`${title} - Bitcoin Institute`}
  description={description}
  lang={lang}
  alternateJa={absoluteUrl('/novel/', 'ja')}
>
  <div class="container novel-page">
    <header class="hero">
      <p class="eyebrow">Novel</p>
      <h1>Genesis<br /><span class="subtitle">— The Disappearance of the Founder and the Promise</span></h1>
      <p class="tagline">The Will Bitcoin Left Behind and the Quantum Shock</p>
    </header>

    <section class="lead">
      <p>
        Satoshi Nakamoto.<br />
        Only the name remained. No face, no voice, no nationality, not even an age.<br />
        In the spring of 2011, he vanished after leaving behind a two-line email.
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <p>I've moved on to other things.<br />It's in good hands with Gavin and everyone.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        — Why 21 million?<br />
        — Why did he leave?<br />
        — Why is Bitcoin different from every cryptocurrency that followed?
      </p>
      <p>
        Tokyo, 2025. Three questions raised at a crypto conference are the point where the story begins.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Historical fiction, grounded in the record</h2>
      <p>
        On the night of September 15, 2008, as Lehman Brothers filed for bankruptcy, a developer
        who had already been writing code for more than a year looked at his screen. On October 31,
        a nine-page paper reached the cryptography mailing list through Tor. On January 3, 2009,
        the genesis block was inscribed, and Bitcoin began running while the world knew nothing.
      </p>
      <p>
        The following August, 184.467 billion BTC — coins that should not have existed — appeared
        on the network. In the quiet hours that followed the patch, the creator began to see the
        contradiction of his own presence. In 2014, the day <em>Newsweek</em> reported it had
        "found" the creator of Bitcoin, a single post appeared on P2P Foundation. In 2016, a man
        walked out claiming "I am Satoshi." In March 2024, a London courtroom walked him back off.
      </p>
      <p>
        This novel is a work of fiction grounded in public records: the Bitcoin whitepaper,
        the cryptography mailing list, BitcoinTalk, private correspondence with Martti Malmi,
        Mike Hearn, Adam Back and Hal Finney, and the full record of <em>COPA v. Wright</em>.
        Emails, forum posts, hashes inscribed on the blockchain — the story is stitched
        from fragments that can be verified, and reads the space between them as the choices
        of one developer.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Timelines that cross</h2>
      <p>
        The narrative moves between several timelines. Each scene can be read on its own,
        but they converge, eventually, into a single line.
      </p>
      <ul class="timeline">
        <li><strong>2025 · Tokyo</strong><span>Misaki, a 25-year-old office worker, starts tracing the meaning of Satoshi's silence.</span></li>
        <li><strong>2007-2008</strong><span>A developer writes code for eighteen months, known to no one.</span></li>
        <li><strong>Autumn 2008</strong><span>In the middle of the Lehman collapse, a nine-page paper is dropped onto the cryptography mailing list.</span></li>
        <li><strong>January 2009</strong><span>A message is inscribed into the genesis block.</span></li>
        <li><strong>August 2010</strong><span>184 billion BTC shake the network, and an unseen attacker watches.</span></li>
        <li><strong>Spring 2011</strong><span>Satoshi leaves Mike Hearn a two-line email and disappears.</span></li>
        <li><strong>March 2024</strong><span>A London courtroom puts the "false Satoshi" on record.</span></li>
        <li><strong>2041</strong><span>When AI takes hold of quantum computing, Bitcoin faces its gravest trial.</span></li>
        <li><strong>2140</strong><span>On the day the last bitcoin is mined, another message is written into the chain.</span></li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>And this archive</h2>
      <p>
        The site you are reading now — Bitcoin Institute — hosts the primary sources that the
        novel draws from.
      </p>
      <p>
        Satoshi's forum posts, his replies on the cryptography list, private emails with
        Martti Malmi and Mike Hearn, Hal Finney's "Running bitcoin," Laszlo Hanyecz's pizza
        thread, the BitcoinTalk thread on the 184 billion BTC overflow, the judgement in
        <em>COPA v. Wright</em> — all of these are reachable from the
        <a href="/entries/">entries index</a> and the
        <a href="/participants/">figures index</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        You can read the novel first and check the record afterwards, or read the record first
        and let the novel read between the lines. From either direction, the shape of the
        <em>question</em> called Satoshi Nakamoto comes slowly into view.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>About the book</h2>
      <p>
        Author: Shinji Kashihara<br />
        Original language: Japanese (English edition available)<br />
        Published: 2025
      </p>
      <p class="note">
        This work is historical fiction. Dates, quotations, figures, technical specifications,
        and statements attributed to real people as <em>historical fact</em> have been checked
        against public records. Interior monologue, motivations and scene-level detail are
        filled in as fiction.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="buy">
      <h2>Where to read</h2>
      <p class="buy-lead">
        Available on Amazon. <strong>Kindle editions are free to read for
        <a href="https://www.amazon.com/kindle-dbs/hz/signup" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Kindle Unlimited</a> subscribers.</strong>
      </p>
      <ul class="buy-links">
        <li>
          <a href="https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B0GCSLMSWT" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            <span class="edition">English Edition (Kindle)</span>
            <span class="ku-badge">Free with Kindle Unlimited</span>
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B0GDFZNBLK" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            <span class="edition">English Edition (Paperback)</span>
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B0G6MCVMGX" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            <span class="edition">Japanese Edition (Kindle)</span>
            <span class="ku-badge">Free with Kindle Unlimited</span>
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B0GDDL1634" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            <span class="edition">Japanese Edition (Paperback)</span>
          </a>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .novel-page {
    max-width: 720px;
  }
  .hero {
    text-align: center;
    padding: 2.5rem 0 2rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }
  .hero .eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.2em;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
  }
  .hero h1 {
    font-size: 2.2rem;
    line-height: 1.25;
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
  }
  .hero .subtitle {
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    font-weight: normal;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }
  .hero .tagline {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    margin: 0;
  }
  .lead {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
  }
  .lead blockquote {
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent);
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
    padding: 0.25rem 1rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-style: italic;
  }
  .lead blockquote p {
    margin: 0.25rem 0;
  }
  section {
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }
  section h2 {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    padding-bottom: 0.4rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }
  .timeline {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .timeline li {
    padding: 0.5rem 0;
    border-bottom: 1px dashed var(--color-border);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }
  .timeline li:last-child {
    border-bottom: none;
  }
  .timeline strong {
    display: inline-block;
    min-width: 10em;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }
  .note {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    border-left: 2px solid var(--color-border);
    padding-left: 0.75rem;
  }
  .buy {
    background: var(--color-bg-muted, rgba(0,0,0,0.02));
    padding: 1.5rem;
    border-radius: 4px;
  }
  .buy-lead {
    margin-top: 0;
  }
  .buy-links {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0.5rem 0 0;
    display: grid;
    gap: 0.5rem;
  }
  .buy-links a {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: space-between;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    background: var(--color-bg);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 4px;
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .buy-links a:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }
  .buy-links .ku-badge {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    padding: 0.15rem 0.55rem;
    border-radius: 999px;
    background: var(--color-accent);
    color: var(--color-bg);
    white-space: nowrap;
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }
  .buy-lead strong a {
    color: inherit;
    text-decoration: underline;
  }
  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .hero h1 {
      font-size: 1.7rem;
    }
    .hero .subtitle {
      font-size: 1rem;
    }
    .timeline strong {
      display: block;
      min-width: auto;
      margin-bottom: 0.25rem;
    }
  }
</style>
